A great family party recipe! The learned chef from Iowa is correct, however, to add one more view to the Salmonella controversy (as a former microbiologist). Bacteria needs protein and sugar to grow. The common denominator to the salads is the protein, including the eggs in the mayo. Commercial mayo is fine, just be careful with homemade. That's why burger places have outbreaks - the handling of the ground meat. The best advice is, chilled or room temp is a personal choice, but WASH YOUR HANDS when preparing food. That's where the bacteria comes from. It doesn't grow there by itself.

